The elements of a visualization 
データ･ビジュアライゼーションのさまざまな要素についてお話しします。チャートやグラフ、データマップをニュースメディアやソーシャルメディアで目にしたとき、その要素は何か説明できますか？
データ･ビジュアライゼーションはふつう、いくつかの層からできていて、私は一番下の層から説明していきます。まずビジュアライゼーションの最も基礎的な層は「足場」レイヤーと呼ばれています。
「足場」レイヤーはビジュアライゼーションをサポートする全ての要素を含みます。その上にあるのがエンコーディングレイヤーです。すぐ説明するのでちょっとお待ちを。
エンコーディングレイヤーの上には注釈レイヤーがあり、データを（ストーリーの）文脈に整合させるための全てのテキスト要素が配置されます。
一番上の層には、引用符付きの"me"レイヤーがあります。それでは、レイヤーを一つずつ取り上げて説明していきたいと思います。
まずは足場レイヤーです。足場レイヤーとは何なのでしょう。このチャートをご覧ください。これはウォールストリートジャーナルがデザインしました。
トピックは本題ではありませんが、さまざまな部門の失業率に関するものです。ここではチャートのコンテンツではなく、コンテンツをサポートする要素に焦点を当てます。
右上の色分けされた凡例や、軸ラベル、軸そのもの、これが足場レイヤーです。基本的にはこれがコンテンツの表示方法を決めており、あらゆるものを文脈の中に置いているのです。コンテンツの下に足場レイヤーがあるといってもよいでしょう。
コンテンツそのものはエンコーディングレイヤーに相当します。エンコードの概念はビジュアライゼーションの基礎です。
すでに説明したように、データ・ビジュアライゼーションは基本的に、オブジェクトの特定の性質に数字をマッピングすることで構成されます。
これは抽象的なアイデアですが、とても理解しやすいものです。
Let's suppose that you begin with a bunch of numbers, a bunch of figures, a data set, and then you choose an object to represent those numbers, a series of objects to represent those numbers. Let's say a series of rectangles. You have a series of rectangles of the same size and then you have the numbers over here. And then when you map those numbers onto those rectangles, there will be one rectangle per observation in your data set. The height of those bars will change according to the numbers that you have on your data set. The result of doing that is a bar graph, right? This size, not the size, the height, the height of those rectangles will vary in proportion to the data that you had on your data set. In that case, we will say that the encoding that we are using is height. 
So the encoding, the encoding in data visualization is not the object that you choose to represent your data. It is the property of those objects that you vary according to the data. So in data visualization we could use many different kinds of methods of encoding. This is like, by the way, if you want to learn a little bit more about encoding, I discuss them at length in my book, The Truthful Art. There are many different kinds of encoding, one of them is height, right? Like in bar graphs, height or length, length is also used in bar graphs when the bars are horizontal. 
But there are other many encodings, for example, position. You could use as objects to represent your data, you can use little dots and then you can vary the relative position of those dots next to each other in proportion to the data that you have in your data set. In that case, you will say that the encoding is not the dots, the encoding is the position, encoding is position, right? You could use area, for example, when you create, say, maps in which you put bubbles on top to represent your data, unemployment rate in the United States and you have little bubbles that vary in size according to those numbers. The encoding in that case is not the bubble. The encoding in that case is the area, area is the encoding, right? 
Encoding is, sorry, area is also the method of encoding used in a kind of graphic called the tree map. The tree might be sort of that rectangular shape that you have there on the right hand side of the image, right? You show a total, right? That's the big rectangle, and then the subdivisions of that rectangle shows you the, you know, the relative the relative size of the components of that total in that area. In that case, the area is also the encoding of that chart. You can also use angle, right? Like in pie charts the encoding is angle and as a consequence of that, the area of the segments of that pie chart are also, is also proportional to the data that you're trying to, that you're trying to represent. Line weight, for example, is another way to represent your data and then color, color, both color, hue, different colors or color shade, the intensity of those colors can be used to represent your data. But there are many other kinds of encoding, these are just the most common ones in data visualization.
